football?

28:04.216 --> 28:06.451 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Just in this
election, Gwen.

28:06.485 --> 28:10.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This has been going on ever
since Harry Truman
became president suddenly and
didn't even

28:10.856 --> 28:16.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
know about the Manhattan Project
in 1945,
decided he didn't want any
president, future

28:16.728 --> 28:18.697 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
president-elect to be faced with
this.

28:18.730 --> 28:19.831 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And it's just gone on.

28:19.865 --> 28:21.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And some candidates use it a
lot.

28:21.767 --> 28:24.369 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Some candidates don't avail
themselves much.

28:24.403 --> 28:30.175 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But this year, as you said,
partisans have
been attacking both candidates
as being untrustworthy

28:30.208 --> 28:31.977 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
with the information.

28:32.010 --> 28:37.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the Aspen security conference
last week,
James Clapper, the head of --
the DNI, said

28:37.349 --> 28:42.020 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
he had -- quote -- "no
hesitation" and, in
fact, that teams of
professionals had already

28:42.054 --> 28:44.356 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
been assigned to each candidate.

28:44.389 --> 28:46.224 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But there was a lot of
scuttlebutt.

28:46.258 --> 28:51.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There were a lot of spooks and
former spooks,
as I like to describe them, at
this conference.

28:51.730 --> 28:55.968 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there were quite a few
questions, frankly,
about whether Trump would even
avail himself

28:56.001 --> 28:59.237 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of them, since he said, "I know
more about
ISIS than the generals."

28:59.271 --> 29:00.238 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
So...

29:00.272 --> 29:01.440 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: How does it work?

29:01.473 --> 29:02.941 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, do they go to the CIA
and get the
briefing?

29:02.975 --> 29:04.276 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Does the CIA come to them?

29:04.309 --> 29:06.044 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: It's a combo of
both.

29:06.078 --> 29:08.347 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They try to make sure it's a
secure location.

29:08.380 --> 29:12.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Part of it depends on whether
they have asked
for the overview or a deep dive
on one topic.

29:12.851 --> 29:16.321 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, they might just make a hotel
room secure.

29:16.355 --> 29:20.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They might even set up what is
called a SCIF,
which is a special secure
facility, or just

29:20.192 --> 29:21.360 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
sweep it.

29:21.393 --> 29:24.763 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Other times, they have to go to
the local
FBI office.

29:24.796 --> 29:30.535 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the scope of the information
is really
broad, general intelligence
assessments.

29:30.569 --> 29:33.538 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's no discussion of covert
operations,
for example.

29:33.572 --> 29:36.942 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So if someone were to say, well,
who is your
source in the Iranian
government, I'm not

29:36.975 --> 29:38.577 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
allowed to say, sir.

29:38.610 --> 29:43.048 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That changes dramatically when
someone becomes
a president-elect.

29:43.081 --> 29:48.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Then there are teams literally,
I'm told,
at the headquarters of each
candidate, and

29:48.320 --> 29:52.457 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the next morning is delivered to
him or her
the presidential daily brief.

29:52.491 --> 29:55.027 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Which is really the
top-top-secret
documents.

29:55.060 --> 29:57.529 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: That's covert
ops.

29:57.562 --> 29:58.530 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That's a lot.

29:58.563 --> 29:59.531 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's sources and methods.

29:59.564 --> 30:01.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
None of that is going to be
revealed now.

30:01.633 --> 30:05.537 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Has it been ever
withheld from
anyone, this kind of briefing?

30:05.570 --> 30:08.974 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: No, never
withheld, but,
as I said, many don't avail
themselves.

30:09.007 --> 30:10.676 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think Ronald Reagan had only
one.

30:10.709 --> 30:12.511 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Bill Clinton had only one.

30:12.544 --> 30:15.547 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is all according to a great
history log
that is written by John...

30:15.580 --> 30:16.815 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

30:16.848 --> 30:18.617 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Why wouldn't you --
why wouldn't
avail yourself?

30:18.650 --> 30:20.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: As it's been
explained to
me, just think about what we
have got in the

30:20.519 --> 30:22.187 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
next 98 days.

30:22.220 --> 30:24.756 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
These men and women are focused
on winning.

30:24.790 --> 30:26.291 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They're focused on the debates.

30:26.324 --> 30:28.060 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're focused on the money
raising.

30:28.093 --> 30:30.529 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They're focused on the
state-by-state count.

30:30.562 --> 30:35.867 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Their level of interest may not
be as high
as we think it should be.

30:35.901 --> 30:40.005 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Secondly, one senior
intelligence official,
actually Mike Hayden, a former
director and

30:40.038 --> 30:45.711 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
deputy director of the CIA said
-- of the
NSA -- said, you know, they
don't really want

30:45.744 --> 30:49.648 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
too know too much, because they
don't want
to be caught in the debate and
say, can I

30:49.681 --> 30:50.649 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
say that?

30:50.682 --> 30:52.250 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Where did I get that
information?

30:52.284 --> 30:53.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Has that ever
happened, where
someone has inadvertently
blabbed?

30:53.852 --> 30:57.656 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: I asked that,
and apparently
not that anyone could think of.

30:57.689 --> 31:02.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, again, as Hayden said, they
know it's
akin to the death penalty to let
something

31:02.861 --> 31:04.062 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
like that slip.

31:04.096 --> 31:06.598 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But there is -- if I may go
on...

31:06.631 --> 31:08.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
GWEN IFILL: Sure.

31:08.433 --> 31:10.335 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: ... there's a
huge difference
in the level of intelligence
that's given

31:10.368 --> 31:12.137 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
at this stage.

31:12.170 --> 31:18.076 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Mike Morell, former deputy
director and
director temporary of the CIA,
had to brief

31:18.110 --> 31:20.011 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
McCain and Palin.

31:20.045 --> 31:24.382 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he said, so you walk in with
John McCain
from Armed Services Committee
and Intel Committee,

31:24.416 --> 31:29.154 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
one of the great experts in the
Senate, immediately,
it's going very deep.

31:29.187 --> 31:30.989 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He knows a lot.

31:31.022 --> 31:35.794 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But he said, you know, with a
Sarah Palin,
he said it's like national
security 101, and

31:35.827 --> 31:39.164 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's very broad and it's very
general, and
you have got to give a lot of
history.

31:39.197 --> 31:44.402 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that will probably apply
this time with
Trump and Secretary Clinton.

31:44.436 --> 31:48.974 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As one said to me, Secretary
Clinton, she
will probably walk in and say,
so, where were

31:49.007 --> 31:50.776 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
we?

31:50.809 --> 31:53.812 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She's learned these secrets for
a long, long
time, even though not in the
last two years.

31:53.845 --> 31:55.914 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Do vice presidential
candidates
get them as well?

31:55.947 --> 31:57.716 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Yes, they do.

31:57.749 --> 32:00.619 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: So, the only person
of the four
who doesn't have Washington
experience would

32:00.652 --> 32:01.620 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
be Donald Trump.

32:01.653 --> 32:03.221 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: That's right.

32:03.255 --> 32:05.190 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And, therefore,
would be classified
briefing 101, as you put it.

32:05.223 --> 32:06.291 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

32:06.324 --> 32:08.693 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Margaret Warner,
thank you so
much.

32:08.727 --> 32:16.001 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: My pleasure.

32:16.034 --> 32:26.111 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: A series of
federal court decisions
in the last few weeks could
change the rules

32:26.144 --> 32:29.147 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about how many Americans will be
casting votes
this November.

32:29.181 --> 32:31.950 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
William Brangham has the latest
on these rulings.

32:31.983 --> 32:35.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Voting rights
supporters
have won a series of remarkable
victories

32:35.654 --> 32:39.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the last few weeks, what they
contend is
a much-needed pushback against
what they say

32:39.991 --> 32:42.861 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are discriminatory voter-I.D.
laws.

32:42.894 --> 32:47.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Since 2008, 10 states, almost
all governed
by Republican legislatures, have
passed laws

32:47.966 --> 32:52.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
tightening the requirements for
the kinds
of I.D. you need in order to
vote, or made

32:52.170 --> 32:55.373 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
other changes to when and how
votes get cast.

32:55.407 --> 32:59.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But several federal courts have
now ruled
that some of those laws are
discriminatory.

32:59.811 --> 33:04.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On Monday, a federal judge
blocked North Dakota's
voter I.D. law, saying it
impinged on the

33:04.749 --> 33:06.551 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
rights of Native Americans.

33:06.585 --> 33:10.422 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The judge wrote -- quote -- "No
eligible voter,
regardless of their station in
life, should

33:10.455 --> 33:13.058 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
be denied the opportunity to
vote."

33:13.091 --> 33:17.495 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Last Friday, a federal court
ruled that North
Carolina's new voting laws had
intentionally

33:17.529 --> 33:23.168 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
been designed to discriminate
against minorities,
saying -- quote -- "These new
provisions target

33:23.201 --> 33:26.438 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
African-Americans with almost
surgical precision."

33:26.471 --> 33:31.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then, in July, another court
ruled that
Texas' voter-I.D. laws also hurt
minority

33:31.843 --> 33:36.014 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
voters, and they ordered the
laws be changed
before November, saying -- quote
-- "It would

33:36.047 --> 33:42.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be untenable to permit a law
with a discriminatory
effect to remain in operation
for that election."

33:42.187 --> 33:44.589 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Joining me now to wade through
these changes
is U.C.

33:44.623 --> 33:46.758 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Irvine law Professor Richard
Hasen.

33:46.791 --> 33:48.994 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He writes what's called The
Election Law Blog.

33:49.027 --> 33:51.363 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So, Professor, help me
understand this.

33:51.396 --> 33:54.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The courts have been saying, not
so fast,
states.

33:54.933 --> 33:59.204 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Generally speaking, what have
the states been
doing with their voting laws in
recent years?

33:59.237 --> 34:03.108 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICK HASEN, University of
California, Irvine:
Well, most of these, but not all
of these

34:03.141 --> 34:07.779 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
challenges involve new strict
voter identification
laws.

34:07.812 --> 34:14.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Every state has some way of
identifying voters,
but if you narrow the number of
identifications

34:14.386 --> 34:18.623 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that are acceptable, and a lot
of people don't
have those I.D.s, you run the
risk of disenfranchising

34:18.657 --> 34:21.192 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
people who are otherwise
eligible to vote.

34:21.226 --> 34:25.230 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And so in cases out of
Wisconsin, North Carolina,
North Dakota, and Texas, just in
the last

34:25.263 --> 34:30.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
few weeks, we have seen those
laws struck
down, in the case of North
Carolina, or, in

34:30.335 --> 34:34.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the case of these other states,
softened so
that people who lack one of
these narrow forms

34:34.205 --> 34:38.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of I.D. can find a work-around,
a different
way to be able to prove their
identity and

34:38.743 --> 34:40.445 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
cast a ballot.

34:40.478 --> 34:43.014 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: We touched a
little bit
at this on the introduction, but
what is it

34:43.048 --> 34:45.483 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that the courts have been saying
that these
laws do?

34:45.517 --> 34:47.886 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What do they find so
objectionable about them?

34:47.919 --> 34:51.556 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICK HASEN: Well, the rulings
are not all
the same.

34:51.589 --> 34:58.563 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In North Carolina, as you
mentioned, the court
thought that the law was
intentionally discriminatory

34:58.596 --> 35:03.902 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
against African-Americans, that
is not necessarily
that the state of North Carolina
acted with

35:03.935 --> 35:07.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
racial hatred or racial animus,
but they knew
that this law was going to make
it harder

35:07.973 --> 35:13.812 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for African-Americans to vote,
and they did
that anyway, and in part doing
it knowing

35:13.845 --> 35:15.947 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that African-Americans tend to
vote for Democrats.

35:15.981 --> 35:19.951 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this was a Republican
legislature, as
it was in all of the states that
you have

35:19.985 --> 35:24.189 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
mentioned, passing the new
restrictive laws
in order to gain some political
advantage.

35:24.222 --> 35:28.660 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Supporters of
these laws
have been saying all along that
these were

35:28.693 --> 35:30.528 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
made to prevent voter fraud.

35:30.562 --> 35:35.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I know, in the North Carolina
case, the judges
ruled that there was really no
evidence that

35:35.333 --> 35:36.901 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that's happening.

35:36.935 --> 35:40.171 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is there evidence that voter
fraud is happening
or is a problem in other states?

35:40.205 --> 35:44.242 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICK HASEN: Well, you know, it
depends on
the kind of voter fraud that
you're talking

35:44.275 --> 35:46.044 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
about.

35:46.077 --> 35:49.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The term is thrown around
loosely, but the
kind of voter fraud that a voter
identification

35:49.414 --> 35:52.017 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
law would target would be
impersonation fraud.

35:52.050 --> 35:54.853 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I go into the polls pretending
to be someone
else.

35:54.886 --> 35:57.989 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This turns out to be very, very
rare.

35:58.023 --> 36:02.127 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's not the way that, when
elections are
manipulated, that it happens.

36:02.160 --> 36:07.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The kind of fraud that we tend
to see, which
is still rare, falls into one of
two categories.

36:07.265 --> 36:11.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Either it's election officials
doing something
to mess with the vote-counting,
or it's something

36:11.669 --> 36:16.241 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to do with absentee ballots,
such as the sale
of absentee ballots.

36:16.274 --> 36:20.378 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Somebody buys absentee ballots
and then votes
them how they want.

36:20.412 --> 36:26.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These kind of activities are not
at all addressed
by voter I.D. laws, which really
only provide

36:26.851 --> 36:31.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
identification in the polling
place to make
sure that someone who shows up
is who he or

36:31.623 --> 36:33.458 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
she says he is.

36:33.491 --> 36:37.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: But on this
issue of voter
fraud, you have probably been
hearing Donald

36:37.262 --> 36:41.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Trump has been making noises
recently that
he believes this November
election could very

36:41.266 --> 36:43.401 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
well be stolen because of fraud.

36:43.435 --> 36:48.473 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He says if people don't have an
I.D., what's
to stop them from going in and
voting 10 times?

36:48.506 --> 36:50.308 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What's the answer?

36:50.341 --> 36:52.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICK HASEN: Well, that sounds
like someone
-- yes, that sounds like someone
who has never

36:52.243 --> 36:55.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
been to a polling place, because
you just
can't go in and ask for a
ballot, and they

36:55.280 --> 36:56.247 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
will just trust you.

36:56.281 --> 36:57.248 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
