37:21.473 --> 37:24.175 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Is there a
potential that
these recent changes could cause
confusion

37:24.209 --> 37:25.477 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on Election Day?

37:25.510 --> 37:28.146 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICK HASEN: There is certainly
the potential
for confusion.

37:28.179 --> 37:33.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just now today, in Texas, the
state of Texas
and the plaintiffs agreed to a
set of rules

37:33.852 --> 37:38.456 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for how people who lack one of
the narrow
forms of I.D. would be able to
vote, by providing,

37:38.490 --> 37:42.660 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for example, a utility bill or a
different
kind of identification.

37:42.694 --> 37:47.565 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In Wisconsin, they're still
litigating over
what the rules are going to be.

37:47.599 --> 37:51.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in North Carolina, North
Carolina indicated
today they may go as far as the
Supreme Court

37:51.669 --> 37:56.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to try to get their law, which
had been reversed,
put back on the books in time
for November.

37:57.008 --> 38:02.547 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I do think it's a real
danger that, as
we get closer to the election,
voters may

38:02.580 --> 38:07.185 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not know, for example, in Texas,
that if they
lack one of those narrow forms
of I.D., they

38:07.218 --> 38:10.955 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
will still be eligible to vote
if they're
otherwise eligible to cast a
ballot.

38:10.989 --> 38:12.857 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
Rick Hasen from
the U.C.

38:12.891 --> 38:16.094 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Irvine, thank you very much for
being here.

38:16.127 --> 38:23.301 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
RICK HASEN: Thank you.

38:23.334 --> 38:30.275 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: It's that time of
year when many
folks are heading to the beach.

38:30.308 --> 38:35.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But along parts of the Southeast
Coast, vacationers
may run into some unwanted
visitors, as the

38:35.680 --> 38:40.785 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
National Weather Service has
issued hazard
warnings caused by jellyfish
found in Myrtle

38:40.818 --> 38:42.720 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Beach, South Carolina.

38:42.754 --> 38:47.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's temporary, but what's not
are the persistent
numbers of the slimy creatures
populating

38:47.225 --> 38:49.260 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the waters of the ocean.

38:49.294 --> 38:53.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Science correspondent Miles
O'Brien reports,
just in time for the summer, for
our weekly

38:53.698 --> 38:57.202 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
series on the Leading Edge of
science and
technology.

38:57.235 --> 39:05.643 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: On beaches, in
harbors and
beneath bays all over the world,
jellies are

39:05.677 --> 39:07.145 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on a roll.

39:07.178 --> 39:12.417 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it appears it's a stinging
rebuke of us
from Mother Nature herself.

39:12.450 --> 39:15.620 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JENNY PURCELL, Western
Washington University:
Jellyfish are thriving in
environments that

39:15.653 --> 39:18.790 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
are damaged by the human
activities.

39:18.823 --> 39:24.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Marine biologist
Jenny Purcell
is a research associate at
Western Washington

39:24.162 --> 39:26.297 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
University in Bellingham.

39:26.331 --> 39:33.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She studies huge aggregations,
or smacks,
of moon jellyfish that have
exploded in Puget

39:33.504 --> 39:34.472 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Sound.

39:34.505 --> 39:36.374 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JENNY PURCELL: Human populations
have increased.

39:36.407 --> 39:40.111 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Their pressure on the oceans
have increased.

39:40.144 --> 39:42.647 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the jellyfish populations
have increased.

39:42.680 --> 39:49.520 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So it's very hard to put a cause
and effect
on that, but the correlations
are certainly

39:49.554 --> 39:51.322 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
there.

39:51.356 --> 39:53.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: There is plenty
of anecdotal
evidence that it's happening,
but arriving

39:53.658 --> 39:57.195 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at hard numbers is like nailing
jelly to a
wall.

39:57.228 --> 40:01.799 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNY PURCELL: Because there
have been so
few jellyfish scientists,
there's a critical

40:01.833 --> 40:04.202 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
shortage of jellyfish data.

40:04.235 --> 40:08.673 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We don't know how many jellyfish
or even what
jellyfish are there.

40:08.706 --> 40:15.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: But at aquariums
all over the
country, there is plenty of
concrete proof

40:15.079 --> 40:16.781 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
jellyfish fascinate us.

40:16.814 --> 40:18.549 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CHILD: Cute, but dangerous.

40:18.583 --> 40:24.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: They are nature's
lava lamp,
a morbidly mesmerizing marquee
attraction.

40:24.322 --> 40:26.357 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEVEN BAILEY, New England
Aquarium: Penguins,
hard to beat penguins.

40:26.391 --> 40:27.358 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Yes.

40:27.392 --> 40:29.327 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
STEVEN BAILEY: Sharks, hard to
beat sharks.

40:29.360 --> 40:36.234 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I would say that jellies
come in a strong
third rather consistently.

40:36.267 --> 40:38.670 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This is hour cold culture room.

40:38.703 --> 40:43.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Steven Bailey is
the curator
of fishes at the New England
Aquarium, smack

40:43.941 --> 40:46.878 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
dab on Boston Harbor, if you
will.

40:46.911 --> 40:49.047 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Bailey is a card-carrying
jellyhead.

40:49.080 --> 40:54.619 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVEN BAILEY: They seem to be
capable of
doing things physiologically
that can't be

40:54.652 --> 40:58.856 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
described by their body plan, by
the structures
that they possess.

40:58.890 --> 41:00.658 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: This got me
intrigued.

41:00.692 --> 41:04.329 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS DOLLER, New England
Aquarium: This is
actually the fifth floor of the
aquarium,

41:04.362 --> 41:06.064 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
considered, like, sort of the
attic.

41:06.097 --> 41:10.001 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: So I asked senior
aquarist
Chris Doller for a
behind-the-scenes tour.

41:10.034 --> 41:11.235 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Where are we now?

41:11.269 --> 41:13.838 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRIS DOLLER: This area is
affectionately
known as Area X.

41:13.871 --> 41:15.640 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

41:15.673 --> 41:19.544 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Area X is the one
of the most
prolific jellyfish nurseries in
the nation.

41:19.577 --> 41:26.884 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They keep about 13 at the
aquarium, a varied
sampling of the 200 large and
800 small types

41:26.918 --> 41:28.553 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of jellyfish in the world.

41:28.586 --> 41:34.726 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They are all cnidaria, in the
same phylum
as anemones and corals among
others.

41:34.759 --> 41:37.829 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CHRIS DOLLER: They're so simple,
yet so complex.

41:37.862 --> 41:39.564 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There's a huge variety of
jellies.

41:39.597 --> 41:41.232 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, you can get very colorful
jellies.

41:41.265 --> 41:43.601 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You can get very iridescent
jellies.

41:43.634 --> 41:45.470 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We have some fluorescent
jellies.

41:45.503 --> 41:52.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: No brain, no
blood, no spinal
cord, just muscle, nerves and
stinging cells

41:52.210 --> 41:56.247 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to kill prey, and inadvertently
bother beach-loving
humans.

41:56.280 --> 41:57.615 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How often do you get stung?

41:57.648 --> 42:02.053 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRIS DOLLER: I try not to, but
it's almost
a daily occurrence.

42:02.086 --> 42:04.989 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: So what does a
grizzled pro
use?

42:05.022 --> 42:06.524 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Warm water or vinegar.

42:06.557 --> 42:08.559 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRIS DOLLER: I think the worst
sting I ever
got was from a flower hat jelly.

42:08.593 --> 42:09.560 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Really?

42:09.594 --> 42:10.995 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CHRIS DOLLER: Yes.

42:11.028 --> 42:13.398 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Some jellies bear
more than
a resemblance to a plant.

42:13.431 --> 42:18.703 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The lagoon and upside down
jellyfish species
are among those that are
photosynthetic.

42:18.736 --> 42:23.608 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Their tissue becomes a home for
algae, and
the jellies use it for energy.

42:23.641 --> 42:25.610 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
All they need is sunshine to
stay alive.

42:25.643 --> 42:31.616 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS DOLLER: That brown that
you see in the
tissue, that's all algal cells,
so they are

42:31.649 --> 42:33.785 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
basically harvesting within
them.

42:33.818 --> 42:36.721 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Yes, the plant is sort of living
in their
tissue.

42:36.754 --> 42:41.159 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Jellyfish
reproduce sexually
and asexually.

42:41.192 --> 42:47.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Most adults send sperm and eggs
into the water,
creating small larvae that grow
into polyps.

42:47.565 --> 42:52.069 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They reproduce by cloning over
and over and
over again.

42:52.103 --> 42:54.572 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Voila, a jellyfish smack.

42:54.605 --> 42:56.707 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're not schooling in the
classic sense,
right?

42:56.741 --> 42:58.543 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CHRIS DOLLER: Right.

42:58.576 --> 43:02.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The way they bud off, it's just
pure numbers,
and then they're all sort of
drifting in the

43:02.313 --> 43:03.347 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
same current.

43:03.381 --> 43:04.482 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They don't migrate
intentionally.

43:04.515 --> 43:06.217 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They just sort of go where the
ocean takes
them.

43:06.250 --> 43:07.218 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: They go with the
flow.

43:07.251 --> 43:08.386 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CHRIS DOLLER: Go with the flow.

43:08.419 --> 43:10.321 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: On the move, they
are constantly
grazing.

43:10.354 --> 43:13.090 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So why are they thriving?

43:13.124 --> 43:18.396 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Many jelly species reproduce
faster in warmer
water, so climate change has an
impact.

43:18.429 --> 43:23.835 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, right now, researchers say
overfishing
is the biggest cause of the
jellyfish bonanza.

43:23.868 --> 43:26.704 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JENNY PURCELL: People have
fished out the
fisheries.

43:26.737 --> 43:29.106 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There is more food left for the
jellyfish.

43:29.140 --> 43:31.509 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: And they will eat
almost anything.

43:31.542 --> 43:36.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They also don't mind living in
troubled waters,
like the huge oxygen-starved
Dead Zone in

43:36.714 --> 43:38.182 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the Gulf of Mexico.

43:38.216 --> 43:42.753 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It is caused by nutrient-rich
fertilizer flowing
down the Mississippi.

43:42.787 --> 43:46.324 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It creates a lot of algae that
depletes underwater
oxygen levels.

43:46.357 --> 43:49.827 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That means fewer fish and more
food for the
jellies.

43:49.861 --> 43:54.065 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, algae blooms and jellyfish
smacks go hand
in hand.

43:54.098 --> 43:58.870 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The guy who has that perfect
lawn right down
to the river, if you will, when
he goes to

43:58.903 --> 44:03.941 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the beach and he gets stung by a
jellyfish,
he actually has some
culpability.

44:03.975 --> 44:06.611 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEVEN BAILEY: I would say that
that's rather
poetic, yes.

44:06.644 --> 44:09.947 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Maybe one
solution is to start
eating them more.

44:09.981 --> 44:15.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In Florida, Georgia and the
Carolinas, a new
kind of fishing industry is
emerging.

44:15.920 --> 44:21.859 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Entrepreneurs are harvesting
cannonball jellies,
pickling them, and exporting
jelly balls to

44:21.893 --> 44:24.595 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Asia, where they are considered
a delicacy.

44:24.629 --> 44:26.063 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Have you ever eaten a jellyfish?

44:26.097 --> 44:27.064 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CHRIS DOLLER: I have.

44:27.098 --> 44:28.099 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: How is it?

44:28.132 --> 44:29.433 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CHRIS DOLLER: Didn't enjoy it.

44:29.467 --> 44:30.434 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Really?

44:30.468 --> 44:32.169 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
No surprise.

44:32.203 --> 44:35.940 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They have no taste, are as chewy
as an eraser,
and pack precious little caloric
value.

44:35.973 --> 44:39.243 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I guess that means we can eat a
lot of them,
if we like.

44:39.277 --> 44:42.613 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there is little concern we
might fish
these guys into oblivion.

44:42.647 --> 44:47.285 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JENNY PURCELL: I think the
jellyfish will
persist after the Armageddon.

44:47.318 --> 44:49.020 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

44:49.053 --> 44:53.024 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: They started on
Earth more
than 500 million years ago, so
why not go

44:53.057 --> 44:54.959 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for a billion?

44:54.992 --> 45:04.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The cockroaches of the sea,
perhaps, but in
the smackdown for fans, the
jellies win, tentacles

45:04.101 --> 45:05.069 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
down.

45:05.102 --> 45:11.742 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Miles O'Brien, the "PBS
NewsHour," Boston.

45:11.776 --> 45:23.354 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
