earlier this summer
at BookExpo America in Chicago.

45:42.640 --> 45:48.179 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Let me ask you to
sort of introduce
what you have done here.

45:48.212 --> 45:49.981 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's a novel, but -- but...

45:50.014 --> 45:52.350 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
COLSON WHITEHEAD, Author, "The
Underground
Railroad": It starts off as a
traditional,

45:52.383 --> 45:54.151 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
realistic about slavery.

45:54.185 --> 45:57.955 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Our main protagonist is a woman
named Cora.

45:57.989 --> 46:02.693 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She's 16, 17 living on a cotton
plantation.

46:02.727 --> 46:08.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when conditions deteriorate,
she's convinced
to flee north on the Underground
Railroad.

46:08.566 --> 46:13.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When I first came up with the
idea many years
ago, I thought, what if the
Underground Railroad

46:13.404 --> 46:16.207 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
was an actual railroad,
literally underneath
the earth?

46:16.240 --> 46:17.208 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

46:17.241 --> 46:18.509 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Well, let's explain that.

46:18.542 --> 46:20.945 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Underground Railroad was a
system, right,
I mean, an idea.

46:20.978 --> 46:24.181 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was people, places, and --
but not a real
railroad.

46:24.215 --> 46:31.288 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
COLSON WHITEHEAD: No, there were
people who
were sympathetic to the slaves
and arranged

46:31.322 --> 46:38.195 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
safe havens and got people
north, hid them,
moved them station to station.

46:38.229 --> 46:40.031 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And it wasn't a literal
Underground Railroad.

46:40.064 --> 46:42.867 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think a lot of people,
when they first
hear about it when they're kids,
at least

46:42.900 --> 46:44.835 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for a few minutes, they think
it's an actual
subway.

46:44.869 --> 46:45.836 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

46:45.870 --> 46:47.705 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

46:47.738 --> 46:50.541 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
COLSON WHITEHEAD: So, the
conceit is, what
if it actually was an
underground train system?

46:50.574 --> 46:51.542 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How would that work?

46:51.575 --> 46:52.810 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And then it...

46:52.843 --> 46:53.644 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And you said this
came to you
many years ago?

46:53.678 --> 46:55.946 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
COLSON WHITEHEAD: About 16 years
ago.

46:55.980 --> 46:57.982 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I knew if I tried it then,
it wouldn't
work.

46:58.015 --> 46:59.583 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I wasn't really up to the task.

46:59.617 --> 47:02.386 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It seemed a bit too big for me.

47:02.420 --> 47:07.324 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I figured, if I got a little
older, or
wiser, became a better writer, I
might be

47:07.358 --> 47:09.794 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
able to tackle it and give it
its due.

47:09.827 --> 47:15.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, every couple years, in
between books,
I would pull out my notes and
think, am I

47:15.266 --> 47:16.233 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ready?

47:16.267 --> 47:17.501 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And each time, it was, no.

47:17.535 --> 47:18.502 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so I would do a different
book.

47:18.536 --> 47:20.037 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Why was the
answer no?

47:20.071 --> 47:21.672 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
In what way were you not ready?

47:21.706 --> 47:23.708 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
COLSON WHITEHEAD: Well, the
subject is so
huge.

47:23.741 --> 47:29.046 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How do you wrap your head
around, completely
around the atrocity of slavery?

47:29.080 --> 47:32.917 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How can you make people that you
care about,
your characters, and put them
into this horrible

47:32.950 --> 47:36.854 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
system and create a realistic
story?

47:36.887 --> 47:41.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think, if I had tried it
16 years ago,
it would have been much
different.

47:41.192 --> 47:42.193 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Now I'm older.

47:42.226 --> 47:44.061 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I have kids.

47:44.095 --> 47:51.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I actually know what it is
to contemplate
having your mother sold in front
of you, having

47:51.268 --> 47:58.142 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
your children sold, seeing your
siblings,
your friends tortured, beaten.

47:58.175 --> 48:04.048 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I think, now I'm in my
mid-40s, I have
more of an idea of what family
means, and

48:04.081 --> 48:08.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that's very much important to
the character
in the book and creating a
realistic family

48:08.252 --> 48:11.222 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
structure for my plantation
characters.

48:11.255 --> 48:15.326 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I was wondering
if you were
worried or putting it off
because of the mix

48:15.359 --> 48:21.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of taking the horror of that
real history
and the reality of those real
lives, but then

48:21.899 --> 48:26.971 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
putting it into this kind of
"Gulliver's Travels,
where there is a kind of fantasy
aspect to

48:27.004 --> 48:27.972 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it.

48:28.005 --> 48:29.907 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
COLSON WHITEHEAD: Well, yes.

48:29.940 --> 48:34.245 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, a couple years ago, the
fantasy would
have been much more pronounced
and much broader.

48:34.278 --> 48:38.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now I think the magic realism
dial is, like,
set on one, as opposed to 10 or
a "Spinal

48:38.849 --> 48:39.950 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Tap"-ian 11.

48:39.984 --> 48:41.752 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

48:41.786 --> 48:44.789 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
COLSON WHITEHEAD: So, each state
she goes
through is a different sort of
state of American

48:44.822 --> 48:46.624 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
possibility.

48:46.657 --> 48:54.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
South Carolina is a benevolent
paternalistic
state, where slaves are given
programs for

48:54.098 --> 48:55.800 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
racial uplifted.

48:55.833 --> 48:57.635 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
North Carolina is a white
supremacist state.

48:57.668 --> 49:01.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they're -- so each stop is a
sort of island
in the "Gulliver's Travels"-type
sense.

49:01.539 --> 49:03.374 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: One that you have
imagined.

49:03.407 --> 49:08.679 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
COLSON WHITEHEAD: Yes, but it's
treated in
a very deadpan and
matter-of-fact way.

49:08.712 --> 49:13.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so while I am stretching the
truth or
tweaking reality, it is still
much grounded

49:13.951 --> 49:16.220 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in what we would call, you know,
the truth.

49:16.253 --> 49:23.561 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Once you opened
it up that
way, was it freeing as a writer?

49:23.594 --> 49:24.562 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
COLSON WHITEHEAD: It was very
liberating.

49:24.595 --> 49:26.330 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes?

49:26.363 --> 49:31.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
COLSON WHITEHEAD: Once you have
a literal
railroad, you're bringing a
fantasy element

49:31.101 --> 49:33.237 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that allows you to do different
things and
play with time.

49:33.270 --> 49:36.607 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so I bring in the Tuskegee
experiments.

49:36.640 --> 49:41.245 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I bring in sort of Nazism and
white supremacy.

49:41.278 --> 49:46.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And even though it takes place
in 1850, I'm
allowed to rove in these
different kind of

49:46.650 --> 49:50.955 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
modes and bring in a lot of
different aspects
of American history in a way
that I couldn't

49:50.988 --> 49:53.023 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
if I was being -- if I was
sticking to the
facts.

49:53.057 --> 49:57.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Because it's all
-- all of
it is fraught territory, right,
for, I mean,

49:57.428 --> 49:58.395 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
today?

49:58.429 --> 49:59.797 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
COLSON WHITEHEAD: It's fraught.

49:59.830 --> 50:04.869 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
People have asked, was I
inspired by Ferguson
or Black Lives Matter?

50:04.902 --> 50:12.977 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, the fact is that white
people in
authority have been abusing the
black body

50:13.010 --> 50:14.812 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for centuries.

50:14.845 --> 50:19.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You don't have to go -- look to
Ferguson to
find someone being gunned down
by policemen.

50:19.750 --> 50:25.022 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the 1850s, before they had
kind of police
force in the South, the
authority was the

50:25.055 --> 50:26.857 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
slave patroller.

50:26.891 --> 50:30.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And a slave patroller could stop
any black
person, free or slave, and
demand to see their

50:30.361 --> 50:32.229 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
papers.

50:32.263 --> 50:34.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if you didn't have your
papers or an excuse
for being off the plantation,
you would be

50:34.698 --> 50:37.902 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
beaten, put in jail, brought
back to your
master.

50:37.935 --> 50:42.439 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's analogous to stop and
frisk right
now.

50:42.473 --> 50:49.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When I was younger, I guess more
threatening-looking,
I would be stopped, I would be
searched.

50:49.680 --> 50:53.284 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
"What are you doing in this
neighborhood?"

50:53.317 --> 50:57.755 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So, I'm not addressing
contemporary ills.

50:57.788 --> 51:04.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm addressing the sort of
problems that have
been around since the beginning
of the country.

51:04.261 --> 51:09.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, hopefully, by the end, I
have learned
something in finishing the book.

51:09.066 --> 51:11.835 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You used to doubt
whether it
was ever going to be finished?

51:11.869 --> 51:13.203 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
COLSON WHITEHEAD: Yes.

51:13.237 --> 51:16.373 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, I think I had a concept
called the
get-hit-by-a-bus draft.

51:16.407 --> 51:22.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's like the draft you
want in case
you get hit by a bus an hour
later.

51:22.246 --> 51:24.114 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Like, will people understand
what you're trying
to do?

51:24.148 --> 51:26.250 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Because you're working on a
novel for years,
and then if something happens to
you in the

51:26.283 --> 51:29.687 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
middle, no one is going to know
what you were
trying to do.

51:29.720 --> 51:33.724 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, if you can just get to that
hit-by-a-bus
draft, that's always a nice...

51:33.757 --> 51:34.725 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

51:34.758 --> 51:36.593 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I never heard
that one before.

51:36.627 --> 51:37.594 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's when you know you're OK?

51:37.628 --> 51:39.396 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
COLSON WHITEHEAD: Yes.

51:39.430 --> 51:42.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It needs to be copy-edited, but
people will
understand what you were trying
-- what you

51:42.266 --> 51:44.068 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
were up to.

51:44.101 --> 51:45.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I don't know if
you want to
put that out in a self-help for
writers book.

51:45.569 --> 51:46.770 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

51:46.804 --> 51:50.107 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
COLSON WHITEHEAD: I think all of
my writing
tips are grim.

51:50.140 --> 51:52.743 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My students definitely have
gotten used to
that.

51:52.776 --> 51:54.078 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right.

51:54.111 --> 51:57.281 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The new novel, the coming novel
